<subSubSection id="FECA55DF678125A21D54B0B3110F4406" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="3F54F02A57E64E004F288A7115AFCF57" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="52989DBEFB7DAD649DE09E289C25C7AA" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">This species is named in honour of Dr. Luciano Paganucci de Queiroz, a great expert on the flora of Bahia, who collected the type material.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3A6781DA05A30AD2E64860F2290A831C" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="distribution and habitat">
<paragraph id="24C968E747BE2E54AEEFFB22219C2731" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EAB57B9568655DE8271B912DE3C9D8FB" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<taxonomicName id="EA829EB112483ECC19CC416D1B9E2B15" authorityName="Gregorio &amp; J. A. S. Costa" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia paganuccii" order="Violales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="paganuccii">
<emphasis id="37FAB6A4F4B36F25B60CF98CA84EE4E2" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Begonia paganuccii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from a single collection from the 
<normalizedToken id="E28EFBEE70E9912723FF8A881B6BB104" originalValue="Área">Area</normalizedToken>
de Relevante Interesse 
<normalizedToken id="0F0508066104F6A0A6C7BBDC2B478CF1" originalValue="Ecológico">Ecologico</normalizedToken>
(ARIE), a protected area in the municipality of Itaberaba (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="FB2E6C0FA2AEB013BAC5C833073A5C7A" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Geographical distribution of three new species of Begonia. A Latin America showing Brazil and Bahia State B Bahia State showing the three political-economic regions of Bahia with new species of Begonia C Political-economic regions of Bahia showing the occurrence of the three new species." pageId="5" pageNumber="6">2</figureCitation>
), region of the Piedmont of 
<normalizedToken id="4A7BBE07F60B6E6638DA80F3D534DE5C" originalValue="Paraguaçu">Paraguacu</normalizedToken>
, growing in seasonal forest at 783 m a.s.l. Nevertheless, agriculture and livestock are common around and within the conservation unit.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CC0BD8939B9BE2169299EADD7A6DB075" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="4D5F12A83A80BCBA53F8D30213FE9208" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7478F5AC4239BCA24F09EC493B451F30" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Flowering and fruiting in August.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B7AD058231E60ACDC23D64E3B4BA333F" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B5CB3E962486FAD2CB56C3E655BD9194" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="23F251BC8D141384A51F61FA561D160A" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<taxonomicName id="BE2BD70B79FC2745495A50A0549E0651" authorityName="Gregorio &amp; J. A. S. Costa" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia paganuccii" order="Violales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="paganuccii">
<emphasis id="828603A78C17E7DDCBB3EEBE8A6D747F" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Begonia paganuccii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterised by a dendritic indumentum, stipules lanceolate, and transversally elliptic leaf-blades, 6- or 7-lobed. Trichomes are quite important in the taxonomy of 
<taxonomicName id="C4939A29D434803B1D53A01A7B69C560" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Violales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Begoniaceae</taxonomicName>
when combined with other morphological information (
<bibRefCitation id="FBB26457931C02ED5C367F47EFA8E5F9" author="Jacques, EL" journalOrPublisher="Universidade de Sao Paulo, Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" refId="B12" refString="Jacques, EL, 2002. Estudos taxonomicos das especies brasileiras do genero Begonia L. (Begoniaceae) com placenta partida. Universidade de Sao Paulo, Brazil" title="Estudos taxonomicos das especies brasileiras do genero Begonia L. (Begoniaceae) com placenta partida" year="2002">Jacques 2002</bibRefCitation>
). Some species in Brazil have dendritic trichomes, such as 
<taxonomicName id="8204C6F7BE9899083A6A263F39BB39AF" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia egregia" order="Violales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="egregia">
<emphasis id="DD60BEF0183F29B7DF4D3536CF5D4699" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Begonia egregia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
N.E. Br and 
<taxonomicName id="232F77F33546DD5D0575969B23091498" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia lindmanii" order="Violales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lindmanii">
<emphasis id="A58A4A25E5B525FAF2F165AF7946FF22" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Begonia lindmanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Brade. 
<taxonomicName id="2545C529EA7B52414E0296D1EB7C3E51" authorityName="Gregorio &amp; J. A. S. Costa" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia paganuccii" order="Violales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="paganuccii">
<emphasis id="6B648B007AB333BAE6D0DDC74E9DE863" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Begonia paganuccii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="EF4B07D523F02DC1C2C19A5D9B2832CF" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia egregia" order="Violales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="egregia">
<emphasis id="B5EB74017F3733E005A1F517460A38EC" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Begonia egregia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the basifixed, lobed and transversally elliptic (vs. peltate, entire and ovate to elliptic) leaf-blade, staminate flowers with 4 tepals (vs. 2) and pistillate flowers with trilocular ovary and 3 styles (vs. ovary tetralocular and with 4 styles). It also differs from 
<taxonomicName id="08093E6F4F1E430554933D46E467D586" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia lindmanii" order="Violales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lindmanii">
<emphasis id="8648B1AA0C16E076C1F2D75E938E1961" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Begonia lindmanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the lobed (vs. entire) leaf-blade, as well as by the many-flowered dichasial cyme (ca. 180 flowers vs. 10-15 flowers) and pistillate flowers with 2 bracteoles (vs. 3 bracteoles). This species can be distinguished from the remaining species of 
<taxonomicName id="2CFA3DB6DE8083728AA23BC2533FAA1F" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia" order="Violales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8A872C4B69FDEC8121F918E715A6A7F5" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Begonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the region where it occurs using the key below. Due to the leaves with cystoliths and the entire placenta, it most likely belongs to the sect. 
<taxonomicName id="914336C6797418DA7C6AC7F7FB6A40E8" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Violales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Pritzelia">
<emphasis id="89AA9F8D9FE3029D8F718CE44EF8A462" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Pritzelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Klotzsch) A. DC.
</paragraph>
